[Event "endgames: Chapitre : 19"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Black "Cornette-Ipatov 2011"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Alex"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "endgames"]
[ChapterName "Chapitre : 19"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h67oha2i/Qq34APSx"]
[FEN "r5k1/5p1p/8/4P1p1/1pp3P1/5P1P/1P6/3R2K1 b - - 0 31"]
[SetUp "1"]

31... Kf8 { A recap: king centralization is one of the key principles of any
endgame. In our case, king is heading to the e6-square after which White might
have problems defending his e5-pawn. } 32. Rc1 Rc8 33. Kf2 c3! { From now on
White's rook is forced to be passive. White cannot win it, since the pawn
endgame is lost. } 34. bxc3 bxc3 35. Ke3 Ke7 { Diagram [#] } 36. f4 { It is a wise
choice for the weaker side to exchange some pawns. } (36. Kd3? Ke6 37. Rxc3 Rxc3+ 38. Kxc3 Kxe5 39. Kd3 Kf4 { and Black wins. }) 36... gxf4+ 37. Kxf4 Ke6 38. Ke4 c2! { Diagram [#] Now White can play only with his king and pawns. White cannot
win the c-pawn because of the black king's penetration to the kingside. } 39. Kd4 h6! { A useful waiting move. Another important endgame principle is applied in
this game: \"not being in a hurry.\" It works because any of White's further
moves might worsen his position. Also, Black is not going to win on the
queenside where he has the passed pawn. That pawn is just a decoy that deflects
white pieces. In fact, Black is going to win by penetrating with his king to the
kingside and picking up the white pawns there $1 } 40. Ke4 (40. h4 { As we can see
from further variations, this move is not helping: } 40... Rc7! { Another useful
waiting move } 41. h5 (41. g5 hxg5 42. hxg5 Kf5 43. Kd5 Rd7+ 44. Kc6 Rd2 $19) 41... Rc8! 42. Ke4 Rc4+ 43. Kd3 Kd5 44. g5 hxg5 45. e6 (45. h6 Rh4 46. Rxc2 Rh3+! 47. Ke2 Kxe5 $19) 45... fxe6 46. h6 (46. Rxc2 Rxc2 47. Kxc2 Ke5 48. Kd3 Kf6 49. Ke3 Kg7 $19) 46... Rh4 47. Rxc2 Rh3+ 48. Ke2 Rxh6 $19) 40... Rc4+ 41. Kd3 { White has to give up space and Black uses it for his own king's
centralization. } 41... Kd5 42. Kd2 (42. Rxc2 { is losing by one tempi $1 } 42... Rxc2 43. Kxc2 Kxe5 44. Kd3 Kf4 45. Kd4 Kg3 46. Ke3 Kxh3 47. Kf3 { Diagram [#] } 47... f6! { if it were Black to move in this position, it would have been a
theoretical draw $1 } 48. Kf4 Kg2 49. Kf5 Kg3 50. Kxf6 Kxg4 51. Kg6 h5 { and Black
wins }) 42... Kd4 { Diagram [#] Further improving the position of his king. } 43. e6 (43. Re1 c1=Q+ 44. Rxc1 Rxc1 45. Kxc1 Kxe5 { and Black wins thanks to his
waiting move f7-f6. }) 43... fxe6 44. h4 Ke5! { The kng is moving to the kingside
to win a pawn there. } 45. Re1+ Kf4 46. Kc1 { White managed to block the pawn with
his king and activate his rook, but it is too late. } 46... Kxg4 47. Rxe6 h5 48. Rg6+ Kxh4 49. Rg2 Kh3 50. Rg1 h4 { In this game, we saw a few important endgame
principles: king centralization, two weaknesses, not being a hurry. and
supporting a passed pawn with the rook from behind. } 0-1


[Event "endgames: TWO WEAKNESSES - Flohr-Vidmar 1936"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[White "TWO WEAKNESSES"]
[Black "Flohr-Vidmar 1936"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "Alex"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "endgames"]
[ChapterName "TWO WEAKNESSES - Flohr-Vidmar 1936"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h67oha2i/9BjA9ZtD"]
[FEN "2r2k2/5p1p/p1p3p1/2Rp4/8/1P2PP2/P5PP/5K2 w - - 0 32"]
[SetUp "1"]

32. Ke2! { First of all, White needs to centralize the king. } (32. Ra5? { Black sacrifices a pawn to activate his rook: } 32... c5! 33. Rxa6 c4 { with excellent chances for a draw. }) (32. b4? { is also not precise: } 32... Ke7 33. Ke2 Kd6 34. Kd3 Rb8!? (34... Kc7!?) 35. a3 Rb5) (32. a4 Ke7 33. a5 (33. b4 Kd6 { [%csl Ga4,Gb4,Ga6,Gc6] })) 32... Ke7 33. Kd3 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gd3d4] } 33... Kd6 34. Ra5! { [%csl Gd6,Gc8,Gc6,Ga6] } (34. Kd4? { in light of } 34... Rb8 35. Ra5 c5+! 36. Kd3 Rb6) 34... Ra8 35. Kd4 { Black must take into account e3-e4 now. } 35... f5!? 36. b4 { White secures control over the c5 and a5-squares and fixes the weaknesses on a6
and c6. } (36. e4 fxe4 37. fxe4 dxe4 38. Kxe4 Re8+ 39. Kd4 Re2 40. Rxa6 Rxg2) 36... Rb8? { Black is being too passive. The rook had to be activated
urgently. } { [%cal Gb8b4] } (36... Kc7! { (/
Kb6) } 37. Kc5 Kb7 38. Kd6 Re8 39. Ra3 { (with the idea Rc3). Now Black should
open up the e-file and invade into the 2nd rank with his rook. } 39... g5! (39... f4? { is bad in view of } 40. exf4 Re2 41. g4 { with f4-f5 to follow. Black cannot
fight against the passed f-pawn because another pawn, on f3, is blocking the
file from rook attacks. }) (39... d4?! 40. exd4 Re2 41. Rc3 Rxg2 (41... Rd2 42. Rc4) 42. Rxc6 Rxh2 43. a4 g5 44. Rc7+! Kb6 45. Rg7!) 40. g3 (40. Rc3 f4 41. exf4 gxf4 { Black maintains enough counterplay, for example } 42. Rxc6 Rd8+ 43. Kc5 d4 44. Re6 (44. Rb6+ Kc7) 44... d3 45. Re1 (45. Re7+ Kc8 46. Re1 Rg8 47. Rd1 Rxg2 48. Rxd3 (48. a4 d2) 48... Rxa2) 45... Rg8) 40... g4! (40... d4?! 41. exd4 Re2 { is dubious here in view of } 42. Ra5! (42. Rc3 Rxh2 { and
the c6-pawn is inviolable. }) 42... h6! 43. a4! (43. Rxf5 Rxa2 44. Rf7+ Kb6 45. Rc7 Rxh2 46. Rxc6+ Kb5) 43... Rb2 44. Rxf5 Rxb4 45. Kc5 Rxa4 46. Rf7+ { and
Black's position is difficult. }) 41. fxg4 (41. f4 Re4 42. Rc3 Rc4 $13) 41... fxg4 42. Rc3 Rf8) 37. a3 Ra8 { The b6-square is perhaps even a worse place for the
rook than a8. } (37... Rb6?!) 38. e4! { White has achieved the maximum on the
queenside and cannot improve his position there anymore. Therefore Flohr applies
a standard method: extending the battlefield $1 After the exchange of the central
pawns, the white king attacks the kingside while the rook gets full control over
the 5th rank. } (38. a4? Rb8) 38... fxe4 39. fxe4 dxe4 40. Kxe4 Ra7? { Black
follows the same fatal policy of passively marking time. } (40... Kc7! 41. h4! (41. Kf4? { gives nothing in view of } 41... Rf8+! 42. Kg3 Kb6) (41. Re5!? Kb6 42. Re7 a5! 43. Rxh7 axb4 44. axb4 Ra4 45. Rg7 Rxb4+ 46. Kf3 Rh4! 47. h3 Rh6 48. Kg4 c5 49. Kg5 Rh8 50. Rxg6+ Kb5 51. Rg7 c4 { / Rc8&lt;=&gt; Levenfish, Smyslov }) 41... Kb6 42. g4 (42. Kf4!?) 42... Rf8 (42... Re8+ 43. Re5) 43. h5 $16 { maintains an
indisputable advantage; the question is solely whether it is sufficient for a
win. }) 41. Kf4 { [%cal Gf4h6] } 41... h6 (41... Ra8 42. Kg5 Ra7 43. Kh6 Ke6 44. g4 { / h4-h5$18 }) 42. h4! Ke6 43. Kg4 (43. Rc5 { [%cal Gc5c6,Ge6d6] }) 43... Ra8 44. h5! g5 { [%csl Gh6,Ga6,Gc6] } (44... gxh5+ 45. Kxh5 { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gh5h6] } 45... Rg8 (45... Rh8 46. Rxa6) 46. g4 $18) 45. g3! { White has created and
fixed a new weakness in Black's camp: the h6-pawn. Prior to returning his king
to the center, he takes control over the f4-square. } (45. Kf3 { is less accurate
in view of } 45... Rf8+ 46. Ke4? Rf4+) 45... Ra7 46. Kf3! Ra8 47. Ke4 { [%cal Ge4f5,Ge4d5] } 47... Ra7 48. Kd4 Kd6 49. Ke4 Ke6 50. Re5+! { Now we can appreciate the principle of two
weaknesses: the black king has to decide which way to go. If he goes to the
kingside, then White will direct his own king towards the queenside and the
other way around. } 50... Kd6 (50... Kf6 { then } 51. Rc5 Rc7 52. Ra5 Ra7 53. Kd4 Ke6 54. Kc5 Rd7 55. Rxa6 Rd3 56. Rxc6+ Kf7 57. a4 Rxg3 58. Rxh6 $18) 51. Re8 c5 (51... Re7+ 52. Rxe7 Kxe7 53. Ke5 $18 { is winning }) 52. Rd8+! (52. Rh8 cxb4 (52... Re7+)) 52... Kc6 (52... Kc7 53. Rh8 cxb4 54. Rh7+ (54. axb4 { of course, also
wins. }) 54... Kb8 55. Rxa7 Kxa7 56. axb4 Kb6 57. Kf5 Kb5 58. Kg6 Kxb4 59. Kxh6 a5 60. Kxg5 a4 61. h6 $18 { Other king retreats lose the c5-pawn. }) 53. Rc8+ Kb6 54. Rxc5 Rh7 { The rook has changed its parking space, but the new one is as
unattractive as the previous. } 55. Re5 Kc6 56. Re6+ Kb5 57. Kf5 Rf7+ { [%cal Gf5e5] } 58. Rf6 { 1-0 White wins. } { [%cal Gf7f6] } 58... Rxf6+ 59. Kxf6 Ka4 60. Kg6 Kxa3 61. Kxh6 Kxb4 62. Kxg5 a5 63. h6 a4 64. h7 a3 65. h8=Q a2 66. Qb8+ Kc3 67. Qa8 Kb2 68. Qb8+ Ka1 69. Qa8 Kb1 70. Kf4 a1=Q 71. Qb8+ (71. Qxa1+ Kxa1 72. g4 Kb2 73. g5 Kc3 74. g6 Kd4 75. g7 Kd5 76. g8=Q+ Kc6 77. Qe6+ Kb7 78. Ke4 Ka8 79. Kd4 Kb8 80. Kc5 Ka8 81. Kb6 Kb8 82. Qd7 Ka8 83. Qb7#) 1-0


