1. Ra4! { Now the black rook is forced to remain passive on the a-file and keep
blocking the white pawn. } 1... Kf6 2. Kf3! { King centralization $1 White cannot
win without bringing in the king. It is nice how all principles work together $1 } 2... Ke5 3. Ke3 h5 4. Kd3 Kd5 5. Kc3 Kc5 6. Ra2! { The best square for the rook.
It supports the a-pawn and protects the f2-pawn. } 6... Kb5 7. Kd4 Rd6+ 8. Ke5 { Introducing principle #3 a bit too early: the principle of two weaknesses.
Black has one weakness on the queenside. That is White's passed pawn. However,
it is not enough to win. So White tries to create the second weakness on the
kingside using the fact that the black king needs to block the a-pawn. } 8... Re6+ 9. Kf4 Ka6 10. Kg5 Re5+ 11. Kh6 Rf5 12. f4?! { Better 12.Kg7 $1 Rf3 13.Kg8 $1
Rf6 14.f4 Rf5 15.Kg7 and White wins (Alekhine). } (12. Kg7! Rf3 13. Kg8! Rf6 14. f4 Rf5 15. Kg7 $18) 12... Rc5! 13. Ra3 Rc7 14. Kg7 Rd7 15. f5 gxf5 16. Kh6 f4 17. gxf4 Rd5 18. Kg7 Rf5 19. Ra4 Kb5 20. Re4! Ka6 21. Kh6! Rxa5 22. Re5 Ra1 23. Kxh5 Rg1 24. Rg5! Rh1 25. Rf5 Kb6 26. Rxf7 Kc6 27. Re7! { 1-0 White wins. } 27... Kd6 1-0


